<highlight>
<T1>four presidents commemorated the 50th anniversary of the civil rights act by honoring the warriors for justice and reflecting on ongoing challenges.</T1>

<T1.1>president barack obama delivered a keynote address at the lyndon b. johnson presidential library.</T1.1>
<T1.1.1>he thanked the "warriors for justice" who fought to end segregation and secure civil rights.</T1.1.1>
<T1.1.2>obama stated that he, michelle, and his daughters have lived out the legacy of lbj's efforts.</T1.1.2>
<T1.1.3>he rejected cynicism about change and reminded that rights must be won and cannot be taken for granted.</T1.1.3>
<T1.1.4>obama expressed concern that past struggles can seem easy from a distance, erasing the pain and difficulty.</T1.1.4>

<T1.2>civil rights hero representative john lewis shared his personal experience at the event.</T1.2>
<T1.2.1>lewis was attacked dozens of times during the civil rights movement, including suffering a fractured skull on the selma bridge.</T1.2.1>
<T1.2.2>he noted that president obama was born during a time when people were arrested just for sitting beside each other on the bus.</T1.2.2>
<T1.2.3>lewis challenged those who say nothing has changed, inviting them to "walk in my shoes."</T1.2.3>

<T1.3>former president jimmy carter addressed persistent disparities despite legislative progress.</T1.3>
<T1.3.1>carter noted there are still gross disparities between black and white people in employment and education quality.</T1.3.1>
<T1.3.2>he expressed concern that too many people are at ease with existing disparities, assuming johnson's work completed the task.</T1.3.2>

<T1.4>former president george w. bush emphasized the importance of education in securing justice.</T1.4>
<T1.4.1>bush warned that the "soft bigotry of low expectations" may be returning.</T1.4.1>
<T1.4.2>he noted that civil rights struggles often took place in educational settings because those who oppress always deny real learning.</T1.4.2>
<T1.4.3>bush stated that through education, we secure justice for the next generation.</T1.4.3>

<T1.5>former president bill clinton focused on the erosion of voting rights and partisan divisions.</T1.5>
<T1.5.1>clinton described efforts to restrict the franchise after 50 years of expanding it as a concern.</T1.5.1>
<T1.5.2>he questioned whether these divisions align with what martin luther king jr. and lyndon johnson fought for.</T1.5.2>
<T1.5.3>clinton warned that lack of unity could put the nation back in the "dustbin of old history."</T1.5.3>

<T1.6>the event honored president lyndon b. johnson, who secured passage of the civil rights act of 1964 and voting rights act of 1965.</T1.6>
<T1.6.1>the civil rights act ended segregation and ushered in the most significant change in america since the civil war.</T1.6.1>
<T1.6.2>the voting rights act was partially eviscerated by the supreme court in 2013.</T1.6.2>
</highlight>